AGI -&nbsp;"I Fathers of the Homeland > were aware of the risks and limits of closure in national areas and dreamed of a Italy open to Europe >, close to the peoples who everywhere in the world were fighting for their own freedom '. The President of the Republic, Sergio Mattarella, writes it in a message sent to the Chief of Staff of Defense, Admiral Giuseppe Cavo Dragone, on the occasion of 2 June.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
"Independence and freedom > are conquests that must be defended every day, in communion of intent and with the ability to cooperate for the common good," said the President of the Republic. "Celebrating the seventy-eight years of the birth of the Italian Republic recalls the values of our identity and a far-sighted and wise Constitution, the result of the extraordinary rebirth that took the steps from the struggle of Liberation," added the head of the state.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
Mattarella emphasized that "our contribution - and in it of the Armed Forces - to the cause of peace and international stability > is more than ever precious in today's situation characterized by devastation and aggression to civil populations in Europe and in the Middle East". "The Republic - Mattarella has written - is grateful to the women and men of the Armed Forces for the absolute tasks in the challenging operating theatres where they are called to operate, within the missions of the United Nations, those fruit of solidarity between the countries of the Atlantic Alliance, the decisions to which we have competition in the European Union".
&nbsp;
The President of the Republic at the Altar of the Homeland &nbsp;> laid a crown of laurel on the tomb of the Unknown Milite > for the celebrations of 2 June. Accompanied by the Defence Minister, Guido Crosetto, the Head of State received the military honors of the inter-force battalion deployed in front of the monument. Then the notes of the Mameli hymn. Meanwhile the rain gives a truce and the celebrations continue, at the moment, with the umbrellas closed.&nbsp; The tricolored arrows colored the sky above the Altar of the Homeland. Then Mattarella, on the historic Lancia Flaminia, went to Via dei Fori Imperiali, in the centre of Rome, for the traditional parade of the Armed Forces. Upon arrival applause from the stands.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
"It is the feast of our democracy, the feast of our unity and our pride," said the premier, Giorgia Meloni, in the margin of celebrations. "It's an important and extraordinary party. It is very important also at this stage because we are in a situation in which so many certainties that we had, like peace, are under discussion and there is need for the Republic and the nation. There is a need for the state to face the situation "with responsibility", he added.
&nbsp;
"This festival is also important because we are in an electoral campaign for the European elections and at the bottom this festival also reminds us of the first idea of Europe, which was an idea of Europe that imagined that its strength, the strength of its union, was also the strength and specificity of the national states". Perhaps we should return to that embryo of European idea and European dream," said the President of the Council.
